  • Possess Drug Paraphernalia [Modifiers: as a Party to a Crime], an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 961.573(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

case called briefly at 2:13pm, and then again at 2:30pm. 
Defendant Domingo I Caballero-Minez in court, in custody, with Attorney Alex Flynn.  ADA Theresa Beck appears for the State of Wisconsin.  
Shawna Stevenoski is sworn as Spanish Interpreter. 

In response to the Court's inquiry, Attorney Flynn verifies that Mr. Caballero-Minez is "well aware" of the immigration-related consequences that shall occur if there is a conviction in this case. 

On Motion of the State, the Court amends Count #1 to Misdemeanor Possession Cocaine contrary to Statute 961.41(3g)(c). 

Maximum penalties recited; Constitutional rights reviewed; plea of " Guilty " entered on Counts #1 and #2; factual basis stipulated and also, the Court finds that a factual basis exists based on the Court's review of the transcript of the Preliminary Hearing testimony; the Court accepts the pleas, finds Mr. Caballero-Minez guilty of both counts, and orders Judgment of Conviction entered.

On both Count #1 and Count #2, the Court withholds sentence, and places Mr. Caballero-Minez on Probation for 18 months, with conditions:

--to serve 90 days [on Count #1 only] in the Jefferson County Jail, to commence forthwith 
--to undergo AODA assessment and follow through with treatment recommendations
--to undergo any other assessment, treatment, and counseling as deemed appropriate by the Agent
--to submit to random urinalyses or other drug testing
--no possession of controlled substances without a valid prescription
--no contact with any known drug offender except for treatment purposes as approved by the Agent, and except for incidental contact as necessary for employment or educational programs as approved by the Agent
--to attempt to obtain/maintain eployment and/or education program as directed by the Agent and accordance with State and Federal law 
--to pay $150 in drug testing fees to the Jefferson County Drug Task Force
--to pay costs of $243 plus $200 DNA surcharge on each count ($886 total)

Days credit for time already served:  201 days
The Court will not allow expungement of this record. 
The Court indicates that it will find that the eventual deportation of Mr. Caballero-Minez would be a "new factor" in regard to a modifying sentence so that the Probation term terminates.
